Stock market records

 The Danish stock market gears up for a spring-time surge in listings
- a surge that may well be stronger and more wholesome than ever before.
February was nothing short of remarkable. In terms of the number of trades completed, it goes down as the most active month ever on the stock market. Never before have so many share trades been completed in one month.
This equates to a daily trade figure of over DKK 5 billion, deriving from over 80,000 trades a day.
Why is this remarkable? Because the stock market acts as a daily opinion poll. The key to the reliability of this poll is the steadily increasing level of activity which is a good indicator of the trust in the market, in Danish companies and in the economy as a whole.
We are all shareholders, in one way or another, and we all have a stake in an active and effective stock market as it represents a unique cog in the socio-economic ‘wheel’.
On the one hand, it ensures that Danes are able to share in the success of Danish companies and, on the other; it makes it possible for Danish companies to make long-term investments. No other model apart from this hundred-year-old, tried and tested stock exchange model, allows the Danish people to become stakeholders in Denmark’s future, and no other model gives companies such good conditions for sourcing capital.
Warming up for listings
What we have witnessed in the last few months has been the warm-up ahead of the coming months’ listings, where a longer period of higher pricing levels and less uncertainty with regard to direction has made the market particularly attractive to new companies.
From an investor’s point of view, it may be worth considering whether or not to participate in new share issues. According to an experiment conducted by our analysts, investors would have achieved far higher returns on their investments by participating in the last five listings on the stock exchange.
 
 
We call this experiment the Twin test, and we have conducted it in two stages:
1. covering the period from the company’s initial stock market introduction to the end of 2013.
2. covering the period from the company’s initial stock market introduction and one month onwards.
Starting with the latter, the comparison shows that if an investor invests a sum, e.g. 1 per cent of the total share capital issued, and sold it a month after listing, they would, after having participated in the last five listings, achieve a return of 18.2 per cent.
If we imagine that this investor had a twin, who in the same period, at each IPO, invested exactly the same amount in the Copenhagen Benchmark Index instead of in the newly listed company, the total return would have been 2.6 per cent.
The tables below show how great a return an investor saw by investing in a listing compared with what the same investment would have yielded in the Copenhagen Benchmark Index.
 
 

As we can see, not all new listings have been equally successful, but the experiment shows that overall, it has paid to participate in the last five listings on NASDAQ OMX Copenhagen.
Now that several large organisations have set their sights on the Danish stock market, investors will have ample opportunity to participate in new listings.
Welcome to NASDAQ OMX



Interview with  Bjorn Sibbern

December 2013
What have you been doing this week?
I spoke to Børsen about our new Intraday Auction for Mid, Small Cap segments and First North to improve liquidity for investors and companies alike. And Wednesday we hosted Margrethe Vestager at Børsforum where we asked her and a prominent allstar panel of speakers the question: Why do we need a strong Danish Marketplace? The answer created a great debate in the audience and kicked off the public leg of the Danish IPO Task Force to improve listing climate for SMEs. We have one of the strongest marketplaces and it seems obvious that we use it to create more growth for SMEs.
 
Did you have a nice summer, what have you done?
I spent two weeks on Playitas. Sports and free time with family. Besides vacation this summer was a bit busier than usual. We saw higher trading activity not least thanks to June’s listing of Matas, which became the sixth largest IPO of the quarter in Europe and received 15,000 new shareholders.

Where do you prefer to travel on your free time?
With over 100 travel days a year I have no preferences – besides spending time with family and doing sports.

How do you like to  revitalize?
I would say running and playing golf.

Which qualifications do you see as the most important among your colleague?
The two most important are commitment and ability to execute. The ability to move a project from A to B.

Your favourite dish?
Risotto

Your favourite  interests?
Sports.

Which are the hardest challenges for your economy today?
The challenges for the Danish economy is the slow growth in BNP. If we as an economy were better at using the dynamics of the Danish equity market, more companies would be able to raise capital for growth and jobs.

What’s your opinion about the  local exchange role/mission in your economy?
The role of the exchange is to provide a marketplace where investors – ordinary citizens like you and me – can invest our savings in listed companies. It is this ability that has made it possible for listed company to raise capital for growth and jobs since 1808 where we were given status as regulated market place for trading equity.

Which challenges do you think will be the hardest for the local exchange?
On the Danish exchange we have seen a remarkeable increase in turnover and we have had three IPOs among the biggest introductions since 2008. But it is still dificult for small companies to access funding. Together with market participants, we need to have a look at how we improve this channel for SMEs and how we use the great potential and momentum we have on the Copenhagen exchange to open the doors for small companies for more liquidity. A case in point is our introduction of a midday auction at year end to improve liquidity in the smaller segments, among other initiatives that we are working on with market participants.

What are you most proud of at work?
Besides maximising the effeciency of the marketplace so that liquidity and shorter spreads have lowered the cost of trading, and the fact that we have had three of the biggest IPOs in the Nordics, I am very proud of the fact that we in december 2012 launched First North Bond Market – an alternative marketplace for issuing corporate bonds for smaller and midsized unlisted companies. That is an attempt at broadening the road to financing and funding for Danish companies as well as contribute to make it easier to diversify investments.
I want to be the forthcoming, CEO do you have any advice for me?
Hard work beats talent!

What do you wish for Christmas?
I look forward to spend time with my family.

What is your New year’s eve resolution? 
My new year’s resolution is to work hard at taking the good momentum we have on the Copenhagen exchange to build a broader equity culture in Denmark. In Denmark there is a lot of passive capital in bank accounts at practically no interest rate. This saved capital should be activated to provide greater yields and provide greater funding opportunities for Danish companies and Danish growth. And then I aim at cutting my marathon time with 13 minutes to 3.30 Hrs.































