Inside Nasdaq: Bjorn Sibbern, Global Information Services, Nasdaq





 






Inside Nasdaq: Bjorn Sibbern, Global Information Services, Nasdaq
Bjorn Sibbern was named Executive Vice President of Global Information Services at Nasdaq last November and has hit the ground running- managing the company’s largest business unit by revenue. He currently resides in his hometown of Copenhagen, but will be relocating to New York City later this month. A Nasdaq veteran, we sat down with Bjorn to learn more about his career and vision for Information Services this year and beyond.Q: You’ve held a number of key roles in the past decade at Nasdaq, can you share with us more about your storied career trajectory?A: I’ve had the pleasure and opportunity to work at Nasdaq for nine years and most recently led and grew our Global Commodities business from Denmark, while also serving as President of the Copenhagen Exchange. Prior, I headed our Nordic Cash Equities and Derivatives Markets. One of my proudest accomplishments was championing the launch and operations of our Futures Exchange (NFX) two years ago. A fun fact that you may not know about me is that I was once a Nasdaq market data customer while serving as the CEO of E*Trade Bank Denmark. It was a positive experience and today I am excited to make the data journey full circle and to now lead our Information Services business that focuses on market data and index products and services.Q: Can you tell us more about the Information Services group- where do you see opportunities to grow the business in 2017?A: Nasdaq Information Services is composed of our Market Data and Index business that provides market data solutions and index benchmarks across all asset classes worldwide. It is one of the company’s largest business units by revenue – representing 22 percent net revenue – and is supported by approximately 120 employees. We offer market data for 90+ solutions and 43,000+ indexes that reach thousands of investment professionals. Having just wrapped up my third month on the job, I see three ways to grow our data and index business this year and beyond. First, by upgrading existing products to provide more value for customers. Second, by building new data & index products and secure further global expansion. And third, by experimenting with machine learning in our Innovation Lab to build analytic products of the future, that we can share with customers today.Q: Technology continues to disrupt the financial services industry- how and what sorts of technologies are disrupting your business?A: Our business is approaching an inflection point where technology is changing the way we think about data and interact with analytics. We are always looking for ways to expand beyond our core data products and are experimenting with advanced analytics and machine learning techniques to develop products that help customers glean stronger insights to make better decisions. In November, we launched Nasdaq Trading Insights – the first product suite to debut from our Innovation Lab – designed to help traders better understand how they perform in the market, how the market behaves, and how they can adjust their strategies to be more successful. We have plans to expand the suite with additional components, including separate products focused on third-party and options data later this year.Q: What index and ETF trends do you see emerging in 2017? What are some index and ETF growth opportunities for Nasdaq?A: The overall trend from active to passive index investing will continue. Last year, approximately 80 percent of active managers failed to meet their benchmark, compared to 60 percent the year prior. Smart beta assets under management (AUM) will continue to grow and chip away from mutual fund AUM. This trend has been strong in the US for years, and we are starting to see these patterns pick up momentum in Europe and in Asia. Our index business is well positioned to continue to take advantage of this trend. We see tremendous opportunity to help asset managers launch ETFs based off our indexes around the world in three ways: by proactively presenting new strategies they may not have thought of, helping them bring to life their own ideas, or by partnering to create something exciting for the investment community.


